    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`:h ]m` provides the following documentation:\n\n```\n\t\t\t\t\t\t*]m*\n]m\t\t\tGo to [count] next start of a method (for Java or\n\t\t\tsimilar structured language).  When not before the\n\t\t\tstart of a method, jump to the start or end of the\n\t\t\tclass.  |exclusive| motion.\n\t\t\t\t\t\t*]M*\n]M\t\t\tGo to [count] next end of a method (for Java or\n\t\t\tsimilar structured language).  When not before the end\n\t\t\tof a method, jump to the start or end of the class.\n\t\t\t|exclusive| motion.\n\t\t\t\t\t\t*[m*\n[m\t\t\tGo to [count] previous start of a method (for Java or\n\t\t\tsimilar structured language).  When not after the\n\t\t\tstart of a method, jump to the start or end of the\n\t\t\tclass.  When no '{' is found before the cursor this is\n\t\t\tan error.  |exclusive| motion.\n\t\t\t\t\t\t*[M*\n[M\t\t\tGo to [count] previous end of a method (for Java or\n\t\t\tsimilar structured language).  When not after the\n\t\t\tend of a method, jump to the start or end of the\n\t\t\tclass.  When no '}' is found before the cursor this is\n\t\t\tan error.  |exclusive| motion.\n\nThe above four commands assume that the file contains a class with methods.\nThe class definition is surrounded in '{' and '}'.  Each method in the class\nis also surrounded with '{' and '}'.  This applies to the Java language.\n```\n\nHowever, these mappings are fairly limited in functionality: they do not work in C++ files with namespace declarations, or Rust files with submodules, etc.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nSimilarly to how some mappings are overriden when an LSP is attached to the current buffer (e.g., `:h K-lsp-default`), it would be great if the `[m`, `]m`, `[M`, `]M` were also overridden with treesitter support when treesitter is enabled for the current buffer.\n\nIn particular, these mappings could be overridden to next / previous start / end of `@function.outer` (or `@function.inner`). Looking at the [compatibility table](https://github.com/nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter-textobjects/blob/main/BUILTIN_TEXTOBJECTS.md), this seems to be supported by virtually all languages that have the concept of functions.\n\nUnlike other text object improvements (e.g., https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/22740), the proposal here does not change the semantics or meaning of the builtin text object, and shouldn't pose any surprises or go against existing muscle memory for users.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I have this remapped as well and it makes a lot of sense. I also have `im`/`am` mapped for selection and it's useful for grabbing anonymous function args in Lua.\n\nBut I'm not sure how this could be upstreamed without the rest of Treesitter Text Objects. I'm fine with having it as a remap if there's not a good answer to that question.",
